---
title: Storing Undirected Graphs in Adjacency Matrices and Adjacency Lists
date: 2023-06-12

An undirected graph is a graph in which every edge is bidirectional. An undirected graph G = <V,E>, where V is a non-empty set, known as a set of vertices, and E is a collection of unordered pairs of elements in V, known as a set of edges.

![fig1]

As shown in the figure, this is an undirected graph.

If we need to store this graph, using an adjacency matrix, we represent the above graph as:

```
    A    B    C    D    E    F    G

A   0    0    1    0    1    0    0

B   0    0    0    0    0    1    0 

C   1    0    0    0    1    0    0

D   0    0    0    0    0    0    1

E   1    0    1    0    0    0    0

F   0    1    0    0    0    0    1

G   0    1    0    1    0    1    0    

```

From this table, we can see that the adjacency matrix of an undirected graph is symmetrical along the main diagonal because the undirected graph does not distinguish direction.

With such an adjacency matrix, we can use the matrix to determine which two vertices have an edge between them, and even use the adjacency matrix to verify whether a graph is an adjacency matrix.

However, the adjacency matrix can only represent simple graphs, i.e., graphs whose edges and points have no special meaning. So, what kind of data structure should we use if we have such a graph:

![fig2]

In the figure, we can see that this is an undirected weighted graph. Now, if we need to represent such a graph, what kind of data structure should we use?

Perhaps you could say, I will still use the adjacency matrix to store the data, the storage method is as follows:

```
     a    b    c    d    e    f        

a    0   20    1    0   10    9       

b   20    0    5    6    0   11        

c    0    5    0    6    0    0        

d    0    6    6    0   18   14        

e   10    0    0   18    0   10        

f    9   11    0   14   10    0      
```
  
In this case, the values stored in the adjacency matrix have multiple meanings, not only representing the existence of a relationship between two vertices but also knowing what kind of relationship exists. However, things will get complicated, as each edge may have properties such as weight, maximum flow, minimum flow, etc., and our vertices may also have their properties (such as weight), the adjacency matrix is no longer suitable in this case. So, what kind of data structure should we use to deal with this, which can cope with complex situations?

This is where we can consider the adjacency list:

![fig3]


This is an adjacency list used to represent an undirected graph. In the figure, all vertices are sequentially numbered 0,1,2,3, and then in the linked nodes, the number represents the next node. As this is an undirected graph, there are repetitions. When a new property needs to be added to the vertex of this undirected graph, we only need to add a property to the node. In this view, the expandability is obviously better than the adjacency matrix. Some people may be wondering, this adjacency list still can't solve the problem of increasing edge properties, right? For this question, let's look at the following figure:

![fig4]

In this figure, the node in the adjacency list has an additional property specifically for storing edge values. In this view, whether it's the addition of point object properties or the addition of edge properties, we can implement them through the adjacency list.

However, friends who have really used related data structures will find a problem. When dealing with problems, we often need to get an edge for operations. But in the case of only one vertex, getting an edge from the adjacency list is a painful thing. Each time we get it, we need to traverse all the edges connected to that vertex, which is very time-consuming and memory-consuming. Although the adjacency matrix can be accessed randomly, it cannot handle complex tasks. So, what should we do?

Throughout the history of computing, we have encountered many such problems. The page replacement algorithms and scheduling algorithms in computer operating systems are both in situations where they have advantages in opposing aspects (A is proficient in A field, but not familiar with B field; B is proficient in B field, but not familiar with A field). In this view, we can learn from the solutions of our predecessors. We can first store the complete graph using the adjacency list, and then only use the adjacency matrix to store the connections between points. In this way, we can take advantage of both, at the cost of a bit more space to store the adjacency matrix.
